Though the simulations are performed at absolute zero, this theoretical model correctly reproduces the essential room temperature electronic photophysics of DP-Mes—quantitative singlet fission from S1 to 1TT, mediated by coupling to charge-transfer states which are not directly populated—and provides full dynamic information about the nuclear motion48 (see Supplementary Fig. 11 for a brief discussion of temperature effects). Based on the simulations we can examine the role of each vibrational mode during the singlet fission reaction in DP-Mes and its contribution to the experimentally observed impulsive Raman spectrum. To accurately compare the calculations to the experimental results it is important to note that the recorded impulsive Raman intensity depends on the dimensionless displacement parameter, Δ, of the state-specific vibrational normal modes of DP-Mes according to Eq. (1), where ω denotes vibrational frequency.1I∝Δ2ω2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
